es\/8f53295a73878494e9bc8dd6c3c7104f_large.jpg","images\/8f53295a73878494e9bc8dd6c3c7104f_medium.jpg","images\/8f53295a73878494e9bc8dd6c3c7104f_thumbnail.jpg","images\/76dc611d6ebaafc66cc0879c71b5db5c_large.jpg","images\/76dc611d6ebaafc66cc0879c71b5db5c_medium.jpg","images\/76dc611d6ebaafc66cc0879c71b5db5c_thumbnail.jpg","images\/9b8619251a19057cff70779273e95aa6_large.jpg","images\/9b8619251a19057cff70779273e95aa6_medium.jpg","images\/9b8619251a19057cff70779273e95aa6_thumbnail.jpg","images\/82aa4b0af34c2313a562076992e50aa3_large.jpg","images\/82aa4b0af34c2313a562076992e50aa3_medium.jpg","images\/82aa4b0af34c2313a562076992e50aa3_thumbnail.jpg","images\/65ded5353c5ee48d0b7d48c591b8f430_large.jpg","images\/65ded5353c5ee48d0b7d48c591b8f430_medium.jpg","images\/65ded5353c5ee48d0b7d48c591b8f430_thumbnail.jpg","images\/02522a2b2726fb0a03bb19f2d8d9524d_large.jpg","images\/02522a2b2726fb0a03bb19f2d8d9524d_medium.jpg","images\/02522a2b2726fb0a03bb19f2d8d9524d_thumbnail.jpg"],"slug":"spring-2014","name":"Spring 2014","id":4,"articles":[{"id":98,"ad":false,"title":"Panel Discussion with the Editors of NBC's 'Hannibal'","excerpt":"The last few years of C.C.E. panels is great indication of the wealth of editing talent in Canada, with shows like The Borgias, Flashpoint, Hatfields and McCoys, to name a few.","content":"<p><span style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">The last few years of C.C.E. panels is great indication of the wealth of editing talent in Canada, with shows like The Borgias, Flashpoint, Hatfields and McCoys, to name a few. A quick glance at the imdb pages of our full members reveals just how much great work is being done here. Not only are these major network shows edited by Canadians, they&#8217;re edited in Canada; &#8216;Hannibal&#8217; being the most recent addition to the list. I feel that this is an important distinction, and a promising one.<\/span><\/p>\n<p>There&#8217;s an undeniable tinge of curiosity around a panel discussion like this, if not for the wall-to-wall talent the show employs, then at least how a show like &#8216;Hannibal&#8217; might operate differently being run by larger American counterparts; this panel did not disappoint on either front.<\/p>\n<p>&#8216;Hannibal&#8217; is an NBC TV series adapted using characters from the &#8216;Red Dragon&#8217; novels by Thomas Harris, and the title role is deftly portrayed by Mads Mikkelsen. It is shot and edited in Toronto. Roger Mattiussi C.C.E. moderated an open discussion that did a great job of encompassing both production process and the craft of the final show. The editors at large were Michael Doherty, C.C.E., Stephen Phillipson and Ben Wilkinson C.C.E.. All three spoke highly of the creator and show-runner, Bryan Fuller (Pushing Daisies, Wonderfalls, Dead Like Me) who maintains a distinct vision for the show. &#8216;Hannibal&#8217;, for anyone who hasn&#8217;t seen it, sets itself apart from other police procedurals (not to mention the filmic adaptations of Red Dragon) through its tone. The locations and mise-en-scene are austere, the camerawork exceedingly deliberate, the editing more calculated than you&#8217;ll see on other network shows; these elements all reinforce the sense of control in Dr. Hannibal Lecter&#8217;s world. This is what makes the show interesting, the FBI agent with whom we should be identifying, while obviously talented, is seemingly unstable and unaware of his true proximity to evil. Unlike other adaptations, this is not the world of the FBI, this is Hannibal&#8217;s world. In contrast to Graham&#8217;s instability, Hannibal&#8217;s precision is terrifying and more often than not, charming.<\/p>\n<p>The show uses &#8220;deconstruction&#8221; scenes where FBI special investigator Will Graham (Hugh Dancy) visualizes the crime scene unfolding in reverse. Gifted with &#8220;pure empathy&#8221; Graham is able to adopt an external point of view. The visual unpacking of violent elements allows him to break the crime down step by step to give context to the clues that are left behind. Michael Doherty, C.C.E. talked about the construction of these scenes and the challenge of balancing their use in the show. They&#8217;re beautiful sequences, with reversed slow motion blood splatter, psychic pendulums wiping any unnecessary elements from the crime scene, and pulsing music and sound design. Once the audience understands this motif, they understand Graham&#8217;s mind. Later on in the episode or series these sequences can be simplified.<\/p>\n<p>The show shoots for eight days and the editors cut daily alongside production with a ninth day for polishing the assembly. The show is largely written to accommodate Bryan Fuller&#8217;s preference for more sustained shots, held moments and slower pacing but occasionally assemblies come in long. Another challenge the editors face on &#8216;Hannibal&#8217; is how to cut a show down to time while maintaining the relevant space in the scenes. One example was a 59-minute assembly needing to meet 43-minutes for broadcast. In a case like this, the answer is most cases is not editing out dialogue, or removing air from heads or tails of scenes, it&#8217;s choosing the scenes that will be lost entirely. This must be quite the daunting task given the quality of writing on the show.<\/p>\n<p>&#8216;Hannibal&#8217; has a very classical style that Bryan Fuller is committed to maintaining. Doherty, Phillipson and Wilkinson all agreed that it was Fuller&#8217;s extremely high standards that have elevated the show. He wants things to be great but that doesn&#8217;t mean cutting for shorter attention spans; in fact, quite the opposite. &#8216;Hannibal&#8217; is elegant horror. The elegance is achieved through the luxury of time; time holding on subtle reactions, time waiting for small gestures in a wide shot, and time&#8230; just enough time to be uncomfortable.<\/p>\n","resources":[{"title":"Hannibal - Full Trailer (HD)","id":68,"content":"<p>Full 2-minute international trailer for Hannib